previous games between us had been decided. There is no reason to complain of
a lack of fight in this game either.} 1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 Bb4+ 4. Nbd2 b6
5. a3 Bxd2+ 6. Qxd2 Bb7 7. e3 O-O 8. Be2 d6 9. O-O Nbd7 10. b4 Ne4 11. Qc2 f5
12. d5 $1 exd5 $6 ({9 years earlier I reacted as Black with} 12... e5 $14 {and
I still consider that answer to be correct.}) 13. Nd4 Qf6 14. cxd5 (14. Bb2 $2
{was played by Boris Gelfand in 2005, but after} c5 15. Nc6 d4 16. exd4 Bxc6 {
Black (Moiseenko) was already better as} 17. d5 $4 {is met with} Ba4 $1 $19)
14... Bxd5 15. f3 Ng5 (15... c5 $2 16. fxe4 Bxe4 17. Qa2+ $18) 16. Bb2 $1 {
White doesn't need to take care for a while about the pawn, as numerous
threats make Black's life very difficult.} Qg6 (16... c5 17. Nb5 Qe7 18. Nc7
Qxe3+ 19. Kh1 $16) (16... Ne6 17. Rad1 Nxd4 (17... Qg5 18. Bc4 Bxc4 19. Qxc4
Rae8 20. e4 $18) 18. Rxd4 Bf7 19. Qxc7 $16) 17. Bd3 $5 {The most interesting
and the strongest, but also simple} (17. Qxc7 {leads to advantage for White.}
Ne5 18. Rac1 f4 (18... Rf7 19. Qc3 $16) 19. e4 Bxe4 20. h4 $1 (20. fxe4 f3 $11)
20... Nh3+ 21. Kh1 Bd3 (21... Qg3 22. fxe4 $16) 22. Bxd3 Nxd3 23. gxh3 Nxc1 (
23... Nxb2 24. Rg1 Qf6 25. Ne6 g6 (25... Rf7 26. Qc8+ $1 Rxc8 27. Rxc8+ Rf8 28.
Rxf8+ Qxf8 29. Nxf8 Kxf8 30. Rc1 $18) 26. Ng5 Qg7 27. Qxg7+ Kxg7 28. Ne6+ $18)
(23... Qg3 24. Qc4+ (24. Rc2 $4 Qxh3+ 25. Kg1 Rac8 $19) 24... Kh8 25. Rc2 Qxh3+
26. Kg1 Rf6 (26... Qg3+ 27. Rg2 Nxb2 28. Qe2 Qxh4 29. Qxb2 $16) 27. Qxd3 Rg6+
28. Qxg6 hxg6 29. Rg2 $16) 24. Rg1 Rfc8 25. Qe7 $1 Re8 (25... Qf7 26. Qg5 $1
$18) 26. Qb7 Qf7 27. Qxf7+ Kxf7 28. Bxc1 $16) 17... Ne5 18. Nxf5 $1 ({To take
an exchange with} 18. Bxf5 Nexf3+ (18... Ngxf3+ $5 19. Kh1 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 Rxf5
21. Rxf5 Be6 $14) 19. Kh1 Nxd4 20. Bxd4 $14 {would be a sin.}) 18... Ngxf3+ {
The biggest weakness of Black's position is the unprotected Ra8. And it is not
