1. d4 Nf6 2. c4 e6 3. g3 Bb4+ 4. Bd2 Be7 {Black loses a tempo, but forces
White's bishop to occupy the unfortunate d2-square. Eventually, White will
lose a tempo as well.} 5. Bg2 d5 6. Nf3 O-O 7. O-O c6 {This is one of the most
solid schemes against the Catalan.} 8. Bf4 (8. Qc2 {is an old theoretical
continuation which is out of fashion nowadays.}) 8... b6 9. Nc3 Bb7 (9... Ba6
10. cxd5 cxd5 11. Rc1 Nc6 (11... Bb7 {is safer, but there are few who want to
lose a tempo voluntarily.}) 12. Nxd5 $1 Qxd5 13. Ne5 Nxd4 14. Bxd5 Nxe2+ 15.
Qxe2 Bxe2 16. Bxa8 Rxa8 17. Rfe1 Bb5 18. Rc2 Nd5 19. Rec1 $14 {In this endgame
White can torture his opponent with chances to succeed, especially when there
is Kramnik on the white side... 1-0 Kramnik,V (2744)-Topalov,V (2788)/Dortmund
2005/CBM 108 (41)}) 10. Rc1 Nbd7 11. Nd2 {The idea of this move is to play the
e2-e4 advance which might yield White some more space.[%cal Ge2e4]} (11. cxd5
cxd5 12. Nb5 Ne8 13. Qb3 a6 14. Nc7 Rc8 15. Nxe8 Rxe8 16. a4 Rc6 17. Rxc6 Bxc6
18. Rc1 Qa8 19. e3 Rc8 $11 {1/2-1/2 Radjabov,T (2670)-Izoria,Z (2573)/Antalya
2004/CBM 101 (40)}) 11... Nh5 {A typical move harassing White's bishop.} (11...
c5 12. Nb3 a6 $6 (12... Rc8 {is playable for Black.}) 13. dxc5 Nxc5 14. Nxc5
Bxc5 15. Bg5 h6 16. Bxf6 Qxf6 17. cxd5 $16 {1-0 Romanishin,O (2562)-Poetsch,K 
(2194)/Bad Wiessee 2002/EXT 2003 (33)}) 12. cxd5 {A retreat with the bishop to
e3 totally contradicts White's ideas in this position, therefore he has to go
forward.} exd5 {The only recapture.} (12... cxd5 $2 {is refuted by} 13. Bc7 $1
Qxc7 14. Nxd5 Qd8 15. Nxe7+ Qxe7 16. Bxb7 {wins a pawn.}) (12... Nxf4 $2 13.
dxc6 Nxg2 14. cxb7 Rb8 15. Kxg2 Rxb7 {again with a healthy extra pawn for
White.}) 13. e3 Nxf4 14. gxf4 {The change of pawn structure has weakened a bit
the shelter for White's king, but increased the control over the centre. I
believe that White has a slight advantage here, as his knights are more mobile
than his opponent's bishops.} Nf6 15. Nf3 c5 $6 {This move basically fits
Black's plan. However, at this specific moment is very risky, since Black is
not yet fully developed and prepared for a clash in the centre. The point is
that Zoltan Gyimesi was repeating my last years' game against Arutinian, which
went exactly the same way and ended in a somewhat disappointing draw around
move 20...[%csl Rd5]} (15... Qd6 16. Ne5 Qe6 {would have been logical followed
by developing the rooks. In this case a long-term positional fight would be on.
}) 16. Ne5 {Now White is threatening to take on c5 followed by Qd1-b3 and
Rf1-d1 after which Black is most likely to collapse in the centre. Therefore,
his following move is practically forced.} c4 17. Nxc4 $1 {This is not the win
of a pawn, but an exchange sacrifice, and finally, a novelty! I remember that
during the game versus Arutinian (see below) I considered this move, but
eventually went for the mediocre 17.b3 which spoiled my initiative.} (17. b3 $6
Ba3 18. Rb1 Bb4 19. Qc2 cxb3 20. Rxb3 Ba5 $1 21. Rc1 $13 {1/2-1/2 Postny,E 
(2616)-Arutinian,D (2552)/Cappelle la Grande 2007/CBM 117 ext}) 17... Ba6 18.
Ne5 Bxf1 19. Qxf1 {The Pd5 is doomed to fall, so White will get two pawns for
the exchange.} Rc8 20. Nxd5 $1 Nxd5 {This way Black keeps his bishop, but he
could also keep his knight on the board.} (20... Rxc1 21. Nxe7+ Qxe7 22. Qxc1
$14) 21. Rxc8 Qxc8 22. Bxd5 Bf6 $2 {It is hard to believe, but this natural
move is a serious mistake. The bishop had to go the other way.} (22... Bd6 $1
23. Qc4 (23. Nc6 Qf5 24. Bg2 Qc2 $132) 23... Qf5 {This is the point. Black can
defend Pf7 and avoid the exchange of queens.} 24. Qd3 Qh5 25. Bf3 Qh6 $14 {It
is obviously nicer to play this position as White. However, it will be very
hard to make progress by pushing forward central pawns, since White's king is
vulnerable. The presence of queens on the board will always yield Black
reasonable counterchances.}) 23. Qc4 $1 {The difficulty in this move lies in
the understanding that swapping queens is in White's favour. In the
forthcoming endgame White's king will be safe and will assist the central
pawns to march forward.[%csl Rf7]} Qxc4 $6 {It was still possible to avoid the
exchange of queens, though under unfavourable circumstances.} (23... Bxe5 $2
24. Bxf7+ $1 Kh8 25. Qxc8 Rxc8 26. fxe5 $18 {[%csl Gd4,Ge5]}) ({Considering
what happened in the game later, it is easy to recommend such a passive move as
} 23... Qe8 $1 {However, Black should avoid the exchange of queens at any
price. White would keep a stable advantage in this case, but would still be
far from winning.}) 24. Bxc4 $8 (24. Nxc4 $2 {would spoil everything in view of
} Rd8 25. Bc6 Bxd4 $1 26. exd4 Rxd4 27. b3 Rxf4 $11 {Black's rook + pawn are
no worse than White's minor pieces.}) 24... Bxe5 {Black can't tolerate such a
strong knight.} 25. fxe5 Rc8 26. b3 $18 {The only opened file, the c-file, is
safely blocked. White's central pawn mass is very compact and well protected.
Sooner or later White will create two connected passers which will bring him a
win. Black's only counterplay is connected with attacking the Ph2, but is
insufficient against precise play.[%csl Gd4,Ge3,Ge5,Gf2]} Kf8 (26... Rc6 27. h3
$3 Rg6+ 28. Kh2 Kf8 29. d5 f6 (29... Ke7 30. f4 {followed by Bc4-d3 kicking
out the rook. This is the point of 27.h3, all the squares along the "g" file
are under control.}) 30. e6 Ke7 31. e4 Rg5 32. f4 Rh5 33. Be2 Rh6 34. e5 $18)
27. a4 {Just a useful move preventing the possibility of b6-b5 punch.} (27. f4
$2 b5 $1 28. Bxb5 Rc2 $132 {[%csl Gc2,Rg1]}) 27... f6 28. f4 Ke7 29. Kg2 fxe5 (
29... g5 30. f5 $18 {followed by e3-e4 and White will even get three connected
passers!}) 30. fxe5 Rc6 {This is Black's best chance. The rook is going to
attack the Ph2.} (30... Rf8 31. Bd3 g6 32. Kg3 $18 {followed by e3-e4, d4-d5
etc.}) 31. d5 Rg6+ 32. Kf3 Rh6 33. Kg3 Rg6+ (33... Rh5 34. e6 Kd6 35. e4 Re5
36. Bd3 {White is winning here as well, because soon Black will run out of
moves. For instance:} g6 37. h3 h6 38. Kf4 Rh5 39. Be2 Re5 40. Bf3 a5 41. Bg4
Rg5 42. h4 Re5 43. Ke3 h5 44. Bf3 g5 45. hxg5 Rxg5 46. Kf4 Re5 47. Be2 h4 48.
Bg4 $18) 34. Kf4 Rh6 35. d6+ Kd7 36. Bb5+ Ke6 37. Bc4+ {Gaining some time on
the clock.} (37. Be2 $4 g5+ $1 38. Kxg5 Rxh2 {and White's advantage belongs to
history.}) 37... Kd7 38. Be2 {White needs to transfer the bishop to the
diagonal h3-c8. For this purpose it is necessary to give up the Ph2.} Rxh2 39.
Bg4+ Kc6 40. Bf3+ Kd7 41. Bg4+ Kc6 42. b4 $1 {An important resource. The
following b4-b5 check will drive away the black king.} Rf2+ 43. Ke4 a6 (43...
g6 44. b5+ Kc5 45. Bf3 Rd2 46. Kf4 h6 47. Kg3 $1 {robbing the rook of the f2
square.} Rd3 48. Bc6 Rxe3+ 49. Kf4 Rd3 50. d7 $18 {[%cal Ge5e6]}) 44. b5+ axb5
45. axb5+ Kc5 (45... Kxb5 46. d7 Rd2 47. e6 $18) 46. Bf5 $1 {It is necessary
to prevent the rook from going to f8. Meanwhile, Black's king has no moves and
the kingside pawns do not help either.} Ra2 (46... g6 47. d7 $1 gxf5+ 48. Kd3
Rf1 49. Ke2 $18) 47. Bxh7 {The rest is easy.} Rf2 48. Bf5 Rh2 49. Bg6 Rd2 50.
Be8 Ra2 51. Kf5 Ra8 52. Bc6 1-0

